<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,297,391]" box="[160,285,297,322]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,285,297,322]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,297,391]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">
This new species is named for its subuncus projection, which has a distinct duckbill shape, and thus the Latin word for duck, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St Laurent and Giustii" authorityYear="2019" box="[635,687,367,391]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anas">
<emphasis box="[635,687,367,391]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">anas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is used.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,451,754]" box="[160,262,451,476]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,451,476]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,451,754]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">
Like several other new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dyari" authorityYear="1910" box="[551,658,487,511]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[551,658,487,511]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Zaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
named herein, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St Laurent and Giustii" authorityYear="2019" box="[841,922,487,511]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anas">
<emphasis box="[841,922,487,511]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Z. anas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from a specific locality in the Amazonian rainforest. Most 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burmeisteri" authorityYear="1878" box="[751,903,522,546]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mimallonidae</taxonomicName>
known to inhabit this biome are widespread throughout the relatively homogeneous habitat (St Laurent pers. obs.). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dyari" authorityYear="1910" box="[338,445,591,615]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[338,445,591,615]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Zaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be an exception in the family, with an apparent high degree of micro-endemism within an otherwise expansive habitat. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St Laurent and Giustii" authorityYear="2019" box="[934,1103,626,650]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anas">
<emphasis box="[934,1103,626,650]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Zaphanta anas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="St Laurent &amp; Giusti, 2019" authorityName="St Laurent &amp; Giusti" authorityYear="2019" box="[160,335,660,684]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elephanticula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[160,335,660,684]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Z. elephanticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[345,437,660,684]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described below, are the only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dyari" authorityYear="1910" box="[801,908,660,684]" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Zaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,908,660,684]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1228">Zaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known to be sympatric; thus, perhaps it is no surprise that these two species belong to distinct morphological groups within this genus.
</paragraph>
